# Sell Your Time for Sats
What if booking a time slot and paying for it were the same moment?

---

There's something broken about how we sell our time. You send someone your availability. They pick a slot. And then the actual transaction — the part where money moves — becomes a separate problem. A follow-up email with a payment link. A bank transfer that takes days. A processor that skims a percentage off every hour you worked.

The booking and the payment are two different events. But they don't have to be.

## When payment becomes the booking

Imagine a guitar teacher in Buenos Aires. She gives online lessons to students across three continents. Right now, coordinating time zones is the easy part — it's getting paid that's complicated. Different currencies, different processors, different rules depending on where the student lives.

With LNCalendar, she shares a single link. A student in Tokyo picks a Tuesday afternoon slot, scans a QR code, and pays. The appointment is confirmed the moment the sats arrive. No invoicing. No currency conversion headaches. No waiting for a transfer to clear before confirming the session.

The same link works for her student in Lagos and her student in Berlin. Lightning doesn't care about borders.

## It's simpler than it sounds

LNCalendar is a small extension inside LNBits. You set your days, your hours, your price — and it gives you a public page. That's it. Anyone with the link sees your open slots. They pick one, they pay, it's booked.

There's no account creation for the person booking. No onboarding flow. No credit card form. The payment itself is the only step that matters, and it takes about five seconds.

Unpaid bookings clean themselves up after 24 hours. If someone changes their mind before paying, the slot quietly becomes available again.

## The use cases that open up

A developer doing paid code reviews. A community organizer charging for workshop seats. A bitcoiner offering consulting hours to newcomers. A podcast host selling guest slots.

These are all people who have time to offer but no reason to pay Calendly $10/month plus Stripe's cut on every transaction. They just need a calendar and a Lightning wallet.

LNCalendar runs on your own LNBits instance. You can price in sats or in fiat — the student sees a number they understand, you receive bitcoin. Multiple schedules can flow into different wallets if you want to keep things organized.


